<AiPage
  title="What is a context window?, tokens, limits &amp; how to manage it | KB Cafe"
  description="A clear explainer of the AI context window: what tokens are, what fills the window (system prompt, history, retrieved docs, output), why it runs out, and how to manage it."
  path="/what-is-a-context-window"
  eyebrow="AI Explained · Concept"
  h1="What is a context window?"
  tagline="A model's context window is its working memory, the total amount of text it can consider at once. Understanding it explains most of why AI apps behave the way they do."
>
  <h2>The short version</h2>
  <p>
    A <strong>context window</strong> is the maximum amount of text, measured in <strong>tokens</strong>: that a language model can take into account at one time. It covers <em>everything</em> in a single
    request: the system prompt, the conversation so far, any documents you&rsquo;ve pasted or retrieved,
    <em>and</em> the response the model is generating. If the total would exceed the window, something has
    to give, older text gets dropped, or the request is rejected. The window is the model&rsquo;s
    short-term memory, and it is finite.
  </p>

  <h2>What&rsquo;s a token?</h2>
  <p>
    Models don&rsquo;t read characters or words, they read <strong>tokens</strong>, chunks of text the
    model&rsquo;s tokenizer produces. A token is roughly <strong>¾ of a word</strong>, or about
    <strong>4 characters</strong> of English, but it varies: common words may be one token, rare words and
    code split into several, and non-English text often uses more. &ldquo;Context window = 128,000
    tokens&rdquo; means about 90,000&ndash;100,000 words of working space, shared across input and output.
  </p>

  <h2>What fills the window</h2>
  <p>Every request packs several things into the same budget:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>System prompt</strong>: the instructions that set the model&rsquo;s role and rules.</li>
    <li><strong>Conversation history</strong>: every previous turn the app sends back for continuity. This
      grows with every message and is usually the first thing to overflow a long chat.</li>
    <li><strong>Retrieved context</strong>: documents you paste, or chunks pulled in by
      <a href="/what-is-rag">RAG</a>. This can dominate the budget.</li>
    <li><strong>The output</strong>: the model&rsquo;s reply is generated <em>into</em> the same window, so
      the longer the input, the less room is left to answer.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>See it laid out interactively with the <a href="/context-window-visualizer">Context Window Visualizer</a>.</p>

  <h2>Why it matters</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Things get dropped.</strong> Exceed the window and apps truncate, usually the middle or
      oldest turns, so the model silently &ldquo;forgets&rdquo; what it can no longer see.</li>
    <li><strong>Cost and latency scale with tokens.</strong> A bigger context isn&rsquo;t free: you pay per
      token and wait longer. Stuffing the window &ldquo;just in case&rdquo; is expensive and slower.</li>
    <li><strong>&ldquo;Lost in the middle.&rdquo;</strong> Models attend best to the start and end of a long
      context; facts buried in the middle of a huge prompt are more likely to be missed. Bigger is not
      automatically better.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How context limits are managed</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Summarize</strong> old conversation turns instead of resending them verbatim.</li>
    <li><strong>Retrieve, don&rsquo;t stuff</strong>: use <a href="/what-is-rag">RAG</a> to pull only the
      relevant chunks instead of pasting whole documents.</li>
    <li><strong>Chunk and rank</strong>: break sources into pieces and include only the top matches.</li>
    <li><strong>Reserve output space</strong>: leave enough room for the answer; the reply competes for the
      same budget.</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="note">Context-window sizes range from a few thousand tokens on small/older models to 1&ndash;2
    million on long-context models. Exact limits change often and vary by model, check your provider&rsquo;s
    current docs rather than trusting a remembered number.</p>

  <h2>FAQ</h2>
  <details class="faq"><summary>Is the context window the same as the model&rsquo;s memory?</summary>
    <p>It&rsquo;s the <em>short-term</em> memory for one request. Anything outside the window, earlier in a long chat, or not retrieved, the model simply can&rsquo;t see. Long-term memory across sessions is a separate feature an app builds on top.</p>
  </details>
  <details class="faq"><summary>Does a bigger context window mean better answers?</summary>
    <p>Not necessarily. It lets you include more, but cost, latency, and the &ldquo;lost in the middle&rdquo; effect all push the other way. Relevant-and-concise usually beats large-and-noisy.</p>
  </details>
  <details class="faq"><summary>What happens when I exceed it?</summary>
    <p>Depending on the app, the request errors out or older/middle content is trimmed to fit, so the model answers without the part that was dropped.</p>
  </details>

